## Review: Randomness and Probability Models

- A **random phenomenon** has outcomes that we cannot predict in the short run but that nonetheless has a regular distribution in very many repetitions. (e.g., tossing a fair coin twice)

- The **sample space S** is the set of all possible outcomes of the random phenomenon.

	 (e.g., flip a coin twice, $S=\{HH, HT, TH, TT\}$)

- A **probability model** for a random phenomenon consists of a sample space S and a way to assign probabilities to the outcomes. 

- **An event** is an outcome or a set of outcomes of a random phenomenon. That is, an event is a subset of the sample space.

- The **probability** of an event is the proportion of times the event occurs in many repeated trials of a random phenomenon.

## Review: Probability Rules

- The probability of any event $A$ satisfies $0 \le P(A) \le 1$. 

- If $S$ is the sample space in a probability model, then $P(S) = 1$.

- The **complement** of event A, denoted by A$^c$, consists of exactly the outcomes that are not in A. The	complement rule states that
	$$P(A^c)=1-P(A)$$

- Two events $A$ and $B$ are **disjoint** (mutually exclusive) if they have no outcomes in common, and so they can never occur together. If $A$ and $B$ are disjoint,
	$$P(A\ \text{or}\ B)=P(A\cup B)=P(A)+P(B)$$
- Events A and B are **independent** if the probability of one event occuring is not affected by whether or not the other event occurs.
	$$P(A \ \text{and} \ B)=P(A\cap B)=P(A)\times P(B)$$
	
## Review: Disjoint Events and Independent Events

- \alert{Question: Any two disjoint events are independent?} 

- **Answer:** **FALSE**. In fact, any two disjoint events are NOT independent because if one event occurs, the other event will never occur, by the definition of disjointness.

![Disjoint Events (dependent)](Ch6-Vis1.png){height=20%}

![Non-disjoint Events (can be dependent or independent)](Ch6-Vis2.png){height=20%}

## Random Variables

**Example 1**: Consider flipping a fair coin twice and let $X$ be the number of heads observed.
	\[
	S=\{TT, HT, TH, HH\}\implies
	X=0,1 \ \text{or}\ 2
	\]

**Example 2**: Consider choosing a number at	random between 0 and 1, allowing any number between 0 and 1 as the outcome, and let $X$ be the chosen number. 
	\[
	S= \{\text{all numbers} \ x \ \text{such that}\ 0\le x\le 1\}\implies X\in [0,1]
	\]
	
## Random Variables

- A random variable is a numerical measurement of the outcome of a random phenomenon.

- A random variable is a function that assigns real numbers to outcomes in sample space.

- Random variables are used for modeling unknown quantities in statistical analyses.

- Prior to the trial or observation, the random variable $X$, can take on any value $x$ in the sample space.

- Random variables will be denoted by the uppercase $X$ or $Y$ letters, whereas the particular values that the random variable takes will be denoted by the lowercase $x$ or $y$ letters.

## Types of Random Variables

- A **discrete random variable** $X$ takes a set of separate values that can be given in an ordered list. It can take only a finite number $k$ of different values $x_1, \dots, x_k$ or an infinite (countable) sequence of different values $x_1, x_2, \dots$.

- Examples:

  - the number of heads in four tosses of a coin
  - number of household members
  - number of tosses of a coin until we get a head

- A **continuous random variable** $X$ takes all values in an interval of numbers.

- Examples:

  - waiting time for a credit card authorization
  - interest rate charged on a business loan

## Types of Random Variables

Identify the following random variables as either discrete or continuous:

1) Number of defectives if three parts are tested.
	
	- Discrete
	- Continuous

2) Heights of adult female customers who shop at a clothing store.

   - Discrete
	- Continuous

## Types of Random Variables

